<DOC><DOCNO> AP900209-0040 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-90 0200EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-09 0269</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0278</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall in Tokyo</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar lost ground against the yen Friday,while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell sharply.   The dollar closed at 144.72 yen, down 0.78 yen from Thursday'sclose of 145.50 yen. It opened at 145.08 yen and ranged between144.65 yen and 145.15 yen.   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 214.37-pointgainer Thursday, fell 228.10 points, or 0.6 percent, to close at37,288.14.   Talk of a possible rise in the Bank of Japan's discount rateafter the Feb. 18 elections for the lower house of parliamentdepressed stock prices, dealers said.   Share trading has been light this week in anticipation of theelection, and activity was calmer still Friday morning ahead of thethree-day weekend, traders said.   Both the stock and currency markets will be closed Monday for anational holiday.   Currency dealers said the foreign exchange market was calmthroughout the morning. The U.S. currency's lower start in Tokyofollowed its downswing overnight in New York, where it closed at145.32 yen, down from 145.60 yen.   Although the dollar slipped against the yen, it strengthenedagainst the West German mark as market players sold the mark forprofit-taking and position adjustments from their long, oroverbought, positions, a Bank of Tokyo trader said.   ``The yen is getting slightly stronger against the dollar asinvestors buy the ye against the mark,'' he said, speaking oncondition of anonymity.   Concerns about the implications of a proposal to unify the twoGerman monetary systems, along with profit-taking, helped push themark lower Thursday, traders said.</TEXT></DOC>